  "texts": [
    "We define a Markov kernel p: Z × F X → [0, 1] such that for any measurable setA ∈ F X, p(z, A) = P[X ∈ A | Z = z], meaning p(z, •) is a regular conditional distribution of X given Z = z.",
    "Then for all h ∈ L 2 (X), T h(z) = X h(x) p(z, dx), π Z -a.e.",
    "(11)By the disintegration theorem, for all measurable sets A ⊂ X and B ⊂ Z, the joint distribution admits the disintegrationπ X,Z (A × B) = B A p(z, dx) dπ Z (z),and therefore, the joint distribution π X,Z can be decomposed asdπ X,Z (x, z) = p(z, dx) dπ Z (z),(12)where p(z, dx) is a Markov kernel as defined above.",
    "This decomposition holds in general, even when π X,Z is not absolutely continuous with respect to π X ⊗ π Z.Under Assumption 2, the joint distribution π X,Z is absolutely continuous with respect to the product measure π X ⊗ π Z, and thus admits a densityp(x, z).",
    "= dπ X,Z d(π X ⊗ π Z) (x, z)."
  ],
